    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. could you make it sound a bit warmer though? the candidate was actually really great and we liked them a lot, it was just a super close call. like we'd definitely want to keep them in mind for future roles if something opens up. can you tweak it so it doesn't feel so cold?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's a common situation, and it's important to keep that door open! You definitely want to sound warm, not like you're just sending out a generic rejection notice. We can soften the blow while still being honest about the decision.\n\nHere is a warmer version, heavily leaning into the idea of future opportunities. It's less like a final \"no\" and more like a \"not right *this* time, but maybe later.\"\n\nSubject: Following Up on the Senior Developer Role at [Company Name]\n\nDear [Candidate Name],\n\nThank you again for investing so much time in our interview process for the Senior Developer position. We truly enjoyed every conversation we had with you—you are a genuinely talented developer, and the final round was incredibly difficult because you were such a strong contender! We have decided to move forward with another candidate whose experience aligned perfectly with a very specific, immediate need for this particular role.\n\nPlease know that this was an exceptionally close decision, and we were very impressed with your capabilities. We would absolutely love to keep your profile on file and will certainly reach out if a role opens up in the future that feels like a better fit for your unique strengths. We truly hope our paths cross",
      "source": "target",
